  "prompt": "Did the participants in Plato's Academy call themselves students? How did Plato call them?",
  "response": "In Plato's Academy, participants did not typically refer to themselves as \"students\" in the modern sense of the term. The Academy was more of a communal intellectual gathering than a formal educational institution as we understand today. Members were scholars and philosophers who engaged in discussions and debates about various subjects.\n\nPlato and others would often refer to the members of the Academy as \"companions\" or \"associates\" (Gr. \"synedroi\" meaning companions in council, or \"philosophoi\" meaning philosophers). This reflects the collegial and collaborative nature of the Academy, emphasizing mutual learning and philosophical inquiry rather than a hierarchical teacher-student relationship.",
